{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17592178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17592178"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:11:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:11:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15226"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15226","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15226"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.03,0.09,0.06,0.82]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7917"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65999"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7917"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15226"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51449"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1440"},{"type":"tags","id":"1449"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7662"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19288"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21742"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65999"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her father following genetic counselling. The father was recently diagnosed with colorectal cancer at age 45. The girl has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A colonoscopy reveals several hundred adenomatous polyps carpeting the entire colon, starting from the rectum. Fundoscopy reveals pigmented lesions of the retina.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is very likely the girl has an hereditary cancer syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["MUTYH-associated polyposis","Peutz-Jeghers syndrome","Juvenile polyposis syndrome","Hereditary non-polyposis colorectal cancer","Familial adenomatous polyposis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP). \u003Cstrong\u003EFamilial adenomatous polyposis\u003C/strong\u003E is an autosomal dominant condition caused by mutations in the APC gene, characterised by hundreds to thousands of adenomatous polyps throughout the colon and rectum, typically developing in adolescence or early adulthood. The presence of congenital hypertrophy of retinal pigment epithelium (CHRPE) is a characteristic extra-intestinal manifestation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMUTYH-associated polyposis\u003C/strong\u003E (MAP) is an autosomal recessive condition that typically presents with fewer polyps (usually 20-100) and at a later age than FAP. The number of polyps described in this case and the early age of onset make MAP less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHereditary non-polyposis colorectal cancer\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as Lynch syndrome, is characterised by early-onset colorectal cancer but without the extensive polyposis seen in FAP. Patients typically develop only a few polyps, if any.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJuvenile polyposis syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare hereditary disorder with a SMAD4 genetic mutation. Hamartomatous polyps can be found throughout the digestive tract, particularly in the proximal colon and stomach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeutz-Jeghers syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by hamartomatous polyps throughout the gastrointestinal tract and distinctive mucocutaneous pigmentation, particularly around the lips and oral mucosa. The polyps are typically fewer in number and histologically different from the adenomatous polyps seen in FAP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of FAP involves prophylactic total colectomy, typically in the late teens or early twenties, due to the 100% lifetime risk of developing colorectal cancer if left untreated. Regular surveillance of the upper gastrointestinal tract is also necessary due to increased risk of duodenal and ampullary adenomas.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP) is characterised by hundreds to thousands of colorectal adenomatous polyps developing in adolescence or early adulthood.","FAP requires prophylactic colectomy due to 100% lifetime risk of colorectal cancer if left untreated.","Extra-intestinal manifestations of FAP include congenital hypertrophy of retinal pigment epithelium (CHRPE) and desmoid tumours."],"references":["Meseeha M, Attia M. Colon Polyps. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430761/","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Sandler RS. Epidemiology and risk factors for colorectal cancer. Gastroenterol Clin North Am. 1996 Dec;25(4):717-35. doi: 10.1016/s0889-8553(05)70271-5. PMID: 8960889","Rawla P, Sunkara T, Barsouk A. Epidemiology of colorectal cancer: incidence, mortality, survival, and risk factors. Prz Gastroenterol. 2019;14(2):89-103. doi: 10.5114/pg.2018.81072. Epub 2019 Jan 6. PMID: 31616522; PMCID: PMC6791134","Half E, Bercovich D, Rozen P. Familial adenomatous polyposis. Orphanet J Rare Dis. 2009 Oct 12;4:22. doi: 10.1186/1750-1172-4-22. PMID: 19822006; PMCID: PMC2772987."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51449"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15226"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51449"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-28T15:55:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-28T15:55:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7917"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65999"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups